  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Nadine Schibille's work, *Islamic Glass in the Making*, published by Leuven University Press eBooks, has begun to carve a niche within the academic community, evidenced by two citations in the field of Archaeological and Anthropological Sciences, primarily from Italian scholars.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Nadine Schibille's *Islamic Glass in the Making* has emerged as a noteworthy contribution to the study of archaeological glass, reflecting a growing interest in this specialized area of research. Its academic footprint is underlined by two citations in distinguished venues, specifically in the journal *Archaeological and Anthropological Sciences*. This indicates that the research is not only being recognized but is also influencing ongoing scholarly discussions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the work has gained some visibility outside of strictly academic circles, as evidenced by an online mention tracked through Crossref Event Data. This engagement suggests that *Islamic Glass in the Making* has piqued the interest of broader audiences, highlighting its potential relevance to societal discussions on cultural heritage and material studies.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The publication is backed by the Institut de Recherche sur les ArchéoMATériaux, a recognized institution in the field, which adds credibility to the research. The involvement of such a prominent institution suggests a solid foundation for interdisciplinary collaboration and enhances the work's reputation across related fields.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although this work does not benefit from direct funding support, its citations from Italy signal a specific geographical interest and may encourage future collaborations that could further amplify its reach and impact. Overall, *Islamic Glass in the Making* demonstrates an emerging dialogue within the academic community concerning the significance of material culture, particularly in the context of Islamic history and craftsmanship.</p>",
